statement.p:
(self-adaptive trust region algorithm)
Step 0. Given x0 ∈ Rn, B0 ∈ Rn×n is a symmetric positive-definite matrix, ɛ>0, μo>0, Δ¯>0, Δ0= μ0‖g0‖(Δ0 <<Δ¯), 0<ρ1, ρ2≤1, 0<η0<η1<1, 0<c0<1<c1, k:=0;
Step 1. Compute gk = ∇f(xk), if ‖gk‖ < ɛ, stop;
Step 2. Solve the subproblem (2) giving dk;
Step 3. Compute rk and define r∧k as follows: r∧k={rk, k=0,ρ1rk+(1-ρ1)rk-1, k≥1.
Step 4. Compute xk+1 as xk+1={xk+dk,ifrk≥η0,xk, otherwise .
Step 5. Compute μk+1 as μk+1={c1μk,ifr∧k>η1,c0μk,ifr∧k<η0,μk, otherwise .
Step 6. If rk < η0, set Bk+1 = Bk, otherwise, update the symmetric matrix Bk+1, let Δk+1=min{μk+1‖dk‖2dkT[ρ2B∧k+1+(1-ρ2)B∧k]dk‖gk+1‖ ,Δ¯}, k ≔ k + 1, and go to step 1.

Suppose that dk is an approximate solution of (2), then there is a scalar β ∈ (0, 1], such that
(5)Predk≥β‖gk‖min{Δk, ‖gk‖‖Bk‖}
for all k = 0, 1, 2,…, where dk is an approximate solution of (2) by using Algorithm 2.6 of Nocedal and Yuan (1998).
